Good morning Debbiann, 

Unfortunately the GAP product is not automatic full coverage of the entire remaining balance of your loan. It is a calculation that is done between the selling price of the vehicle on the bill of sale, the Canadian Black Book value at the time of purchase and the time of loss, as well as the insurance settlement that you were provided by your insurance company. It also takes into account the loan amount at the time of loss, as well as a reamortized amount of your loan had all payments been made and no penalties charged to the account. This then gives us a calculation and we provide you with your GAP settlement based on that amount. 

It appears as though there is a discrepancy in the value of the vehicle at the time of loss. Your insurance company offered you far less than the Canadian Black Book value of the vehicle. It appears as though there is a shortfall of about $1500 before taxes. We do not cover the difference in the market value that the insurance company failed to provide during your total loss settlement with them. You may be able to go back to the insurance company and see if they are able to provide you with the difference. 

In order for us to release your cheque to you, we will require the Final proof of loss to be signed by yourself and a witness and sent back to us. I have reattached it in this email as well. 

Please let me know if you have any questions. 

Thanks, 

Sarah Gabor
